It just amazes me that it didn't because I was so close to walking away from this.

00:16:15.080 --> 00:16:17.160
Anyway,

00:16:17.240 --> 00:16:21.160
so I got the dozer and I got the building.

00:16:21.240 --> 00:16:23.160
Another thing that was very,

00:16:23.240 --> 00:16:25.000
very unique was now,

00:16:25.080 --> 00:16:25.880
how am I going to do?

00:16:25.960 --> 00:16:27.360
What am I going to do with this dozer?

00:16:27.439 --> 00:16:28.080
Okay,

00:16:28.160 --> 00:16:30.200
I had it up on the driveway for sale.

00:16:30.280 --> 00:16:37.040
And according to the Richie Brothers auction sales at that time,

00:16:37.120 --> 00:16:43.040
that dozer was selling nationally for as much as $43,000.

00:16:43.120 --> 00:16:43.840
Okay,

00:16:43.920 --> 00:16:50.080
I don't believe that any of the Komatsu D355s were as in good shape as this one was.

00:16:50.160 --> 00:16:53.240
This Komatsu was owned by,

00:16:53.320 --> 00:16:55.840
I believe it was,

00:16:55.960 --> 00:16:57.360
Fresno Tractor.

00:16:57.439 --> 00:17:00.400
And they'd owned it for about six years and had rented it out.

00:17:00.480 --> 00:17:04.079
And this Komatsu was in excellent condition.

00:17:04.160 --> 00:17:08.400
If any Komatsu D355 should have brought $54,000,

00:17:08.480 --> 00:17:09.720
which is what I had it at,

00:17:09.800 --> 00:17:11.440
that one should have.

00:17:11.520 --> 00:17:16.440
I was willing at the auction to take $33,000 for it.

00:17:16.520 --> 00:17:18.720
Couldn't get a bid.

00:17:18.800 --> 00:17:20.119
I got a $20,000 bid.

00:17:20.200 --> 00:17:22.200
That was the only real bid we got.

00:17:22.280 --> 00:17:22.800
Well,

00:17:22.880 --> 00:17:24.760
I had $24,000 in it.

00:17:24.839 --> 00:17:25.839
I'm not going to sell it for $24,000.

00:17:25.879 --> 00:17:26.879
I'm going to sell it for that,

00:17:26.959 --> 00:17:29.879
especially when Richie Brothers says it's worth $43,000.

00:17:29.959 --> 00:17:31.320
So I kept the dozer.

00:17:31.399 --> 00:17:32.879
What was unique,

00:17:32.959 --> 00:17:35.399
after everything's gone,

00:17:35.480 --> 00:17:42.959
I find out that the dozer is two inches shorter than 12 feet

00:17:43.040 --> 00:17:46.320
and will go into the storage building.

00:17:46.399 --> 00:17:50.280
It is one inch narrower than the door.

00:17:50.360 --> 00:17:52.520
If I take the little bottom,

00:17:52.600 --> 00:17:54.720
the edging browsers off,

00:17:54.800 --> 00:17:55.439
or whatever they call them,

00:17:55.480 --> 00:17:56.480
on the dozer blade,

00:17:56.560 --> 00:17:57.880
if I take those off,

00:17:57.960 --> 00:18:00.760
that dozer will go in my storage building.

00:18:00.840 --> 00:18:01.280
So I says,

00:18:01.360 --> 00:18:02.840
well, let's put it inside,

00:18:02.920 --> 00:18:07.320
because then I can build it to do what I am supposed to do.

00:18:07.400 --> 00:18:09.280
And I could not believe it.

00:18:09.360 --> 00:18:13.240
I put up a four by eight piece of plywood on each side of the door

00:18:13.320 --> 00:18:15.280
so that the blade would go through,

00:18:15.360 --> 00:18:16.840
drove that thing up there,

00:18:16.920 --> 00:18:19.360
got out to where the cab was close to the door,

00:18:19.440 --> 00:18:20.840
checked the clearance,

00:18:20.920 --> 00:18:23.040
and I had two, three inches of clearance.

00:18:23.120 --> 00:18:24.320
I drove it right in there.

00:18:24.320 --> 00:18:27.520
It fit through that door so tight,

00:18:27.600 --> 00:18:30.679
you almost had to grease it to get it in there.

00:18:30.760 --> 00:18:35.679
Why did that particular dozer fit in the building?

00:18:35.760 --> 00:18:41.879
Why had I not bought one of the D9s at that Fresno auction?

00:18:41.960 --> 00:18:43.720
It doesn't make any sense.

00:18:43.800 --> 00:18:47.280
You know, a D9's got more horsepower.

00:18:47.360 --> 00:18:51.520
It's probably more dependable than a Komatsu.

00:18:51.600 --> 00:18:52.480
If I'd have bought one of them,

00:18:52.560 --> 00:18:54.240
I'd have never gotten in that building.

00:18:54.280 --> 00:18:58.040
Because they were much taller than the Komatsu was.

00:18:58.120 --> 00:19:00.120
So I'm thinking, well, this is good.

00:19:00.200 --> 00:19:02.480
I get it inside, now I can build it.

00:19:02.560 --> 00:19:04.920
Must be what I'm supposed to do.

00:19:07.080 --> 00:19:10.200
Put it inside under the guise that, you know, it's wintertime.

00:19:10.280 --> 00:19:11.680
I'm not going to be here.

00:19:11.760 --> 00:19:12.600
Everything's sold.

00:19:12.680 --> 00:19:15.360
I don't have a muffler shop anymore.

00:19:15.440 --> 00:19:17.840
I'm going to go snowmobiling.

00:19:17.920 --> 00:19:19.160
I got to keep it out of the weather,

00:19:19.240 --> 00:19:22.840
and I got to keep it away from the frigging criminals down there in Granby

00:19:22.920 --> 00:19:24.000
who are going to come by

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:25.040
and sabotage it,

00:19:25.120 --> 00:19:28.240
which did happen to my place more than once

00:19:28.320 --> 00:19:32.320
in the 10 years, 11 years that I was down there.

00:19:32.400 --> 00:19:34.800
People would steal different things and so forth.

00:19:34.880 --> 00:19:35.880
I mean, it was...

00:19:35.960 --> 00:19:38.960
It's a sick town.

00:19:39.040 --> 00:19:41.240
Other than have the store that I had in Commerce City,

00:19:41.320 --> 00:19:44.000
the muffler shop, which got broke into one time,

00:19:44.080 --> 00:19:46.280
I never had any problems with theft

00:19:46.360 --> 00:19:49.560
in any of the businesses that I ever owned

00:19:49.640 --> 00:19:51.000
or any of the shops that I ever run.

00:19:51.080 --> 00:19:53.840
But in Granby, I had problems.

00:19:54.000 --> 00:19:56.440
And there may be good reasons for that

00:19:56.520 --> 00:19:59.720
because it wasn't sitting on the main street and so forth.

00:19:59.800 --> 00:20:01.640
Whatever, you know.

00:20:01.720 --> 00:20:05.800
But there were more break-ins in my building in Granby

00:20:05.880 --> 00:20:07.920
than any business I have ever owned.

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:09.120
There was four to be exact.

00:20:09.200 --> 00:20:13.040
Three were attempted, I should say,

00:20:13.120 --> 00:20:16.760
where they didn't get in, or if they did, they didn't take anything.

00:20:16.840 --> 00:20:19.720
The one time that they did take anything,

00:20:19.800 --> 00:20:23.120
they stole some wheels off of a street rod that I had

00:20:23.120 --> 00:20:24.800
sitting in front of the building.

00:20:24.879 --> 00:20:26.919
And those people got caught.

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:29.959
And I got restitution from one of them.

00:20:30.040 --> 00:20:30.959
There were three kids.

00:20:31.040 --> 00:20:32.959
One of them paid his restitution.

00:20:33.040 --> 00:20:35.840
The other two, for all I know, they're in jail today.

00:20:35.919 --> 00:20:42.199
But it's just the way that town is.

00:20:42.280 --> 00:20:44.439
It's just...

00:20:44.520 --> 00:20:46.959
You know, they're poor.

00:20:47.040 --> 00:20:50.080
Right now, I think that everybody's probably got a lot of money in their pockets

00:20:50.159 --> 00:20:52.600
because we've had a pretty good economy up here.

00:20:52.600 --> 00:20:55.639
Over the last five or six years.

00:20:55.719 --> 00:20:59.399
But those people all could have a million dollars each.

00:20:59.480 --> 00:21:00.840
They would still be poor.

00:21:00.919 --> 00:21:02.240
They're poor in mind.

00:21:02.320 --> 00:21:03.719
They're poor in pocketbook.

00:21:03.800 --> 00:21:05.360
They're poor in spirit.

00:21:05.439 --> 00:21:07.120
They're poor in heart.

00:21:07.199 --> 00:21:09.560
They're just poor people.

00:21:09.639 --> 00:21:12.000
And I don't know.

00:21:12.080 --> 00:21:13.959
You know, it's...

00:21:14.040 --> 00:21:16.959
They need to stop thinking that they need to...

00:21:17.040 --> 00:21:20.879
They have to get some self-esteem, some self-respect,

00:21:20.959 --> 00:21:22.439
and love their neighbors.

00:21:22.440 --> 00:21:27.480
And not try to deprive them of a right to make a living.

00:21:27.560 --> 00:21:29.640
To have their dreams realized.

00:21:29.720 --> 00:21:35.560
And it's sad that people down there do that.

00:21:35.640 --> 00:21:38.120
And I'm talking about the leaders of the community.

00:21:38.200 --> 00:21:40.120
They keep people down.

00:21:40.200 --> 00:21:42.720
Because if they didn't,

00:21:42.800 --> 00:21:45.800
the real cream of the crop would rise to the top

00:21:45.880 --> 00:21:50.080
and knock them from their position.

00:21:50.160 --> 00:21:52.360
But of course, their definition of cream of the crop

00:21:52.480 --> 00:21:57.080
is to see how devious you can be to screw your neighbor.

00:21:57.160 --> 00:21:59.560
If you're devious enough and you're smart enough

00:21:59.640 --> 00:22:03.280
and wily enough to screw your neighbor,

00:22:03.360 --> 00:22:05.640
then you're the cream and you should be on top.

00:22:05.720 --> 00:22:09.400
You shouldn't earn it through doing honest, hard work.

00:22:09.480 --> 00:22:12.320
You have to get together, have secret meetings.

00:22:12.400 --> 00:22:15.000
You have to spend years conniving,

00:22:15.080 --> 00:22:18.240
waiting for an opportunity to screw your neighbor.

00:22:18.320 --> 00:22:22.120
Well, I've never done it and I ain't planning on doing it.

00:22:22.120 --> 00:22:24.239
Other than what I'm doing now.

00:22:24.320 --> 00:22:28.479
And this will be the first time that I've ever done something like that

00:22:28.560 --> 00:22:30.159
the way they want it to be done.

00:22:30.239 --> 00:22:31.520
The way they do it.

00:22:31.600 --> 00:22:33.280
To do it in secret.

00:22:33.360 --> 00:22:35.280
To do things behind their back.

00:22:35.360 --> 00:22:37.520
To lie to you.

00:22:37.600 --> 00:22:41.199
When you ask them what their plans are and they won't tell you.

00:22:41.280 --> 00:22:42.760
I've had to do that. People ask me,

00:22:42.840 --> 00:22:43.719
what am I doing?

00:22:43.800 --> 00:22:45.840
Oh, I'm not doing anything.

00:22:45.919 --> 00:22:50.199
I spent the whole summer of 2003 in that friggin' building.

00:22:50.280 --> 00:22:51.919
I lived there.

00:22:51.920 --> 00:22:55.880
Without a shower for as much as four days at a time.

00:22:55.960 --> 00:22:58.200
Working on that dozer.

00:22:58.280 --> 00:23:02.440
Getting it prepared to do what I have to do.

00:23:02.520 --> 00:23:05.200
And that's another thing that was so uncanny.

00:23:05.280 --> 00:23:06.280
Talk about getting caught.

00:23:06.360 --> 00:23:07.400
Why didn't I get caught?

00:23:07.480 --> 00:23:08.760
Why haven't I been caught?

00:23:08.840 --> 00:23:11.040
Or why didn't I get caught up to now?

00:23:11.120 --> 00:23:16.520
Last fall, when Travis and Bob go to buy the place,

00:23:16.600 --> 00:23:21.880
they need to have their insurance man come in and see the storage building.

00:23:21.960 --> 00:23:22.960
They want to see inside.

00:23:23.040 --> 00:23:25.160
Now, I had put up a temporary wall.

00:23:25.240 --> 00:23:28.160
And I had insulated that whole building that summer.

00:23:28.240 --> 00:23:29.840
And had started working on this dozer.

00:23:29.920 --> 00:23:32.840
I had this dozer about half done.

00:23:32.920 --> 00:23:37.720
By maybe three quarters done by the time they wanted this insurance guy to come in.

00:23:37.800 --> 00:23:41.320
I had to clean that whole shop up.

00:23:41.400 --> 00:23:43.040
Hide all the steel.

00:23:43.120 --> 00:23:44.200
The welders.

00:23:44.280 --> 00:23:47.360
Hide all that stuff in a little room in the corner.

00:23:47.440 --> 00:23:50.520
I built out of two by fours and canvas.

00:23:50.600 --> 00:23:51.880
And then what did I do?

00:23:51.960 --> 00:23:54.920
I took polypropylene tarps.

00:23:55.000 --> 00:23:58.080
And I covered the dozer.

00:23:58.160 --> 00:24:03.360
Which I had the whole cab armor on.

00:24:03.440 --> 00:24:07.680
I had about half of the engine armor on.

00:24:07.760 --> 00:24:10.680
And I covered it up with tarps.

00:24:10.760 --> 00:24:12.480
And taped it all shut.

00:24:12.560 --> 00:24:16.400
And I says, you know, maybe this is where I'm supposed to get caught.

00:24:16.480 --> 00:24:18.080
They're going to come in here.

00:24:18.160 --> 00:24:19.080
They're going to get nosy.

00:24:19.160 --> 00:24:21.240
They're going to want to know what's under this dozer.

00:24:21.960 --> 00:24:27.640
They're going to find out that I'm building this.

00:24:27.720 --> 00:24:29.800
And somebody's going to go call the cops.

00:24:29.880 --> 00:24:31.040
And they're going to put a stop to it.

00:24:31.080 --> 00:24:32.640
Well, that's the way it's supposed to be.

00:24:32.720 --> 00:24:33.360
Catch me.

00:24:33.720 --> 00:24:34.040
Okay.

00:24:34.880 --> 00:24:37.760
They came in there after I had the shop all cleaned up.

00:24:38.080 --> 00:24:39.400
Had everything put away.

00:24:39.400 --> 00:24:42.520
Had the dozer covered up with these polypropylene tarps.

00:24:43.480 --> 00:24:46.320
I even put a lift in there.

00:24:46.620 --> 00:24:49.220
To lift all this steel onto the dozer.

00:24:49.700 --> 00:24:51.800
This lift was about.

00:24:51.800 --> 00:24:52.800
20 feet long.

00:24:52.879 --> 00:24:54.200
Had a 20 foot arm on it.

00:24:54.280 --> 00:24:56.680
With an electric winch.

00:24:56.760 --> 00:24:58.760
And it swung on a post.

00:24:58.840 --> 00:25:01.000
And that's how I lifted all this steel.

00:25:01.080 --> 00:25:02.080
To get it on there.

00:25:02.159 --> 00:25:02.960
Okay.

00:25:03.040 --> 00:25:04.159
The lift is there.

00:25:04.240 --> 00:25:06.320
So these guys come in.

00:25:06.399 --> 00:25:07.360
Oh, wow.

00:25:07.440 --> 00:25:08.000
What's this?

00:25:08.080 --> 00:25:09.080
This is the dozer.

00:25:09.159 --> 00:25:10.159
Oh, okay.

00:25:10.240 --> 00:25:11.680
What's this lift?

00:25:11.760 --> 00:25:12.320
They say.

00:25:12.399 --> 00:25:16.760
And I say, well, I made up this story about this guy from Minnesota.

00:25:16.840 --> 00:25:20.680
Who was a professor at the university there.

00:25:20.760 --> 00:25:21.639
And was working.

00:25:21.640 --> 00:25:23.920
Working on a system to.

00:25:24.000 --> 00:25:26.560
It was called.

00:25:26.640 --> 00:25:28.920
I can't even think of it right now.

00:25:29.000 --> 00:25:30.200
When you deep freeze things.

00:25:30.280 --> 00:25:37.680
Cyrochirogenics or something like that.

00:25:37.760 --> 00:25:43.080
I said this professor was perfecting a chirogenics cooling system.

00:25:43.160 --> 00:25:47.480
To go in the intake of the diesel engine.

00:25:47.560 --> 00:25:49.720
Which would cool the air.

00:25:49.800 --> 00:25:50.720
And increase.

00:25:50.720 --> 00:25:55.040
And increase the performance of the engine.

00:25:55.120 --> 00:26:01.520
And increase the hourly fuel consumption.

00:26:01.600 --> 00:26:03.480
And they bought it.

00:26:03.560 --> 00:26:05.920
I said, but the lift goes when I leave.

00:26:06.000 --> 00:26:08.360
When this guy comes to pick his dozer up.

00:26:08.440 --> 00:26:10.240
After he's done all this testing.

00:26:10.320 --> 00:26:12.760
We had to put this lift in.

00:26:12.840 --> 00:26:17.080
So we could lift this big 800 pound condenser up on the back.

00:26:17.160 --> 00:26:19.080
Which he had mismeasured.

00:26:19.160 --> 00:26:20.080
And we.

00:26:20.080 --> 00:26:22.159
They had to take it back to Minnesota.

00:26:22.240 --> 00:26:25.679
And then he's got this other evaporator that we had to lift.

00:26:25.760 --> 00:26:26.600
Plus the big.

00:26:26.679 --> 00:26:28.040
The pump has got to go on there.

00:26:28.120 --> 00:26:29.840
We're running that off of a drive.

00:26:29.919 --> 00:26:30.919
An auxiliary drive.

00:26:31.000 --> 00:26:32.960
PTO drive that they've got on the engine.

00:26:33.040 --> 00:26:35.760
I had this whole bullshit story.

00:26:35.840 --> 00:26:37.240
And they went along with it.

00:26:37.320 --> 00:26:38.000
You know.

00:26:38.080 --> 00:26:38.679
I said.

00:26:38.760 --> 00:26:41.560
I couldn't believe it when they walked out the door.

00:26:41.639 --> 00:26:42.760
I'm safe.

00:26:42.840 --> 00:26:45.840
How come they didn't catch me?

00:26:45.919 --> 00:26:49.040
It was right there under their nose.

00:26:49.120 --> 00:26:49.879
Well.

00:26:49.880 --> 00:26:52.760
I wasn't supposed to get caught.

00:26:52.840 --> 00:26:53.840
Not yet.

00:26:53.920 --> 00:26:55.240
Maybe I will.

00:26:55.320 --> 00:26:58.840
Maybe this whole thing will come to stop early.

00:26:58.920 --> 00:27:00.120
That's the way it's supposed to be.

00:27:00.200 --> 00:27:03.920
I will accept that.

00:27:04.000 --> 00:27:06.200
They took away my life.

00:27:06.280 --> 00:27:08.000
They took away my future.

00:27:08.080 --> 00:27:10.480
They took away my hope.

00:27:10.560 --> 00:27:13.640
They took away any desires that I had.

00:27:13.720 --> 00:27:17.800
I cannot operate in a community of people.

00:27:17.880 --> 00:27:19.720
. . .

00:27:19.880 --> 00:27:26.560
that does that to their neighbors.

00:27:26.640 --> 00:27:33.520
I wasted 13 years of my life down there.

00:27:33.600 --> 00:27:40.200
Because the Thompsons were pissed off that I bought that property.

00:27:40.280 --> 00:27:47.880
You put yourself in my shoes and tell me how you would feel at 50 years old.

00:27:47.960 --> 00:27:48.680
. . .

00:27:48.760 --> 00:27:49.840
. . .

00:27:49.919 --> 00:27:57.240
You've wasted 10 years of your life because of someone's malice.

00:27:57.320 --> 00:27:59.000
Because of their jealousy.

00:27:59.080 --> 00:28:00.959
Because of their greed.

00:28:01.040 --> 00:28:04.480
Because of their hate.

00:28:04.560 --> 00:28:05.520
I'm 52 now.

00:28:05.600 --> 00:28:08.439
That's why I talk about 12, 13 years.

00:28:08.520 --> 00:28:12.360
You know, it was 10 years then.

00:28:12.439 --> 00:28:16.760
You know, it just isn't right.

00:28:16.840 --> 00:28:18.360
I cannot.

00:28:18.439 --> 00:28:18.600
. . .

00:28:18.679 --> 00:28:23.679
There used to be a time when I could withstand these types of losses.

00:28:23.760 --> 00:28:24.800
I could never afford them.

00:28:24.879 --> 00:28:27.679
You can never afford to lose money.

00:28:27.760 --> 00:28:31.800
You can withstand it and you can recover sometimes.

00:28:31.879 --> 00:28:37.560
Most of the time I looked at it that way it was because I was young and I was strong.

00:28:37.639 --> 00:28:42.080
And I could go out and physically do the work.

00:28:42.159 --> 00:28:43.520
I'm 52 now.

00:28:43.600 --> 00:28:45.520
I can't do it.

00:28:45.600 --> 00:28:47.320
I can't withstand it.

00:28:47.320 --> 00:28:49.800
I can't recover.

00:28:49.879 --> 00:29:03.080
We're talking about losing $300,000 which along with the sale of the property would have been my retirement.

00:29:03.159 --> 00:29:10.639
Would have let me go on to do other things to make more wealth.

00:29:10.720 --> 00:29:16.520
But when you take 10 years of my life away and just piss it down the drain

00:29:16.520 --> 00:29:20.680
and are happy about it and ecstatic about it.

00:29:20.760 --> 00:29:22.440
No.

00:29:22.520 --> 00:29:26.360
I've taken all I can take.

00:29:26.440 --> 00:29:30.720
How I react, yes it's a reaction.

